<div class="card" id="how-it-works">
<h2><span class="emoji">📊</span>How It Works — Staking, P&amp;L &amp; The Website</h2>

<h3>The staking plan</h3>
<p>Every selection is <strong>1 point, level stakes</strong>. That means the same stake on every single pick — no chasing losses, no doubling up, no variable "confidence" stakes. One point, every time, win or lose.</p>
<p>Why level stakes? Because it's the only honest way to measure if a system actually works. If a tipster varies stakes, they can hide a losing system behind a couple of big-staked winners. Level stakes can't be fudged — the profit is real or it isn't.</p>
<div class="hl">A "point" is whatever you choose it to be. If £10 = 1 point, a +50pt week = +£500. If £2 = 1 point, it's +£100. Scale it to your own bankroll — never bet more than you're comfortable losing.</div>

<h3>How the P&amp;L is calculated</h3>
<p>Profit/loss is worked out at <strong>Betfair Starting Price (BSP)</strong> — the official price every horse is returned at when the race goes off.</p>
<ul>
<li>A <strong>winner</strong> returns its advised price minus the stake.</li>
<li>A <strong>loser</strong> loses the 1pt stake → −1 point.</li>
</ul>
<div class="example">Example: a horse wins at 5.0 BSP → profit = 5.0 − 1 = <strong>+4 points</strong>.</div>
<p>Each day we add up every selection: winners pay out at their actual BSP, losers cost 1pt each. The total is the day's P&amp;L. Add the days together = the running record.</p>
<div class="hl"><strong>Why Betfair SP?</strong> Because it's independently verifiable — nobody can claim a fake price. Every result is settled at the real number the market returned. Wins AND losers are all counted — no cherry-picking the good days.</div>

<h3>📈 The website gives you the full picture</h3>
<p>The Telegram posts give you the selections. The website adds:</p>
<ul>
<li>The <strong>verified results panel</strong> — complete P&amp;L, strike rates and ROI, updated daily</li>
<li>The <strong>tier ratings</strong> (Platinum / Gold / Silver / Bronze) showing how strong each selection is</li>
<li>The <strong>spotlight commentary</strong> on each runner — the form notes and reasoning behind the race</li>
</ul>
<p>If you want to understand <em>why</em> a horse is fancied — the form, the going, the trip — the site has the commentary laid out race by race. The Telegram tips are the quick version; the website is the detail.</p>
</div>

<div class="card" id="how-to-use">
<h2><span class="emoji">📖</span>How To Use The Tips</h2>

<h3>Rank 1 vs Rank 2</h3>
<p>Each race has two selections:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Rank 1</strong> = the model's strongest pick. Higher strike rate (wins more often), usually shorter odds.</li>
<li><strong>Rank 2</strong> = the value angle. Wins less often but at bigger prices — and over time it's actually been the bigger earner.</li>
</ul>
<p>You can back <strong>both</strong>, or just one. Backing both per race covers more winners but costs more in stakes. Backing Rank 1 only is tighter and steadier. Your choice — the record tracks both separately so you can see how each performs.</p>

<h3>Win or each-way?</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Short prices (under ~5.0):</strong> back to <strong>win</strong> — the place part isn't worth much.</li>
<li><strong>Bigger prices (roughly 5.0 and up), especially big fields:</strong> <strong>each-way</strong> is worth considering — you get paid if the horse just places, which cushions the longer-odds picks.</li>
</ul>
<p>The record is kept on <strong>win, level stakes</strong> for consistency — but each-way is a sensible personal choice on the bigger-priced runners, particularly the Rank 2 value picks.</p>

<h3>Staking — keep it simple</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Under 5/1 (6.0): 1pt win. 6.0+: 0.5pt each-way.</strong> Same rule every time.</li>
<li><strong>Set your point size to your bankroll.</strong> A common rule: 1 point = 1–2% of your total betting bank. So a £200 bank → £2–£4 a point. That way a losing run never wipes you out.</li>
<li><strong>Never chase.</strong> Losing days happen — even a profitable system has them. Flat stakes through the downswings is how the edge plays out.</li>
<li><strong>Only bet what you can afford to lose.</strong> This is entertainment with an edge, not income.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Timing your bets</h3>
<p><strong>Back every selection at Betfair Starting Price (BSP).</strong> On the Betfair exchange, tick the "SP" option when you place your bet — you'll get the official starting price the market returns at the off.</p>
<p>The prices shown in each post are a <strong>current-market guide only</strong>. Prices drift and steam through the day, so the morning figure is rarely the final one. The BSP is the real, verifiable price — and it's exactly what our record settles at. Backing at SP means the price you get matches the price our record shows.</p>

<h3>Judge it over weeks, not days</h3>
<div class="hl">One day means little — good or bad. The edge shows over a proper sample. Follow the running record on the site and judge the system over weeks. That's how value betting works.</div>
